<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-109-398  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 109 398.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Gartner Group predicts the future. (Gartner Group Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Gartner Group Inc. (Forecasts).andO;Topic:     TrendsFuture of ComputingComputer industryCommunications Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GARTNER GROUP PREDICTS THE FUTURE 11/08/90 STAMFORD, CONNECTICUT, U.S.A.,andO;1990 NOV 8 (NB) -- The Gartner Group Inc., a major consulting and researchgroup, says that over the next five years, major changes will take placewithin the computer and telecommunications industries.andP;  The revelations, madeat the firm's recent conferences, include a predication that the USinformation systems industry, slowing to a 7 percent growth rate afterseveral years of growth at up to 20%, will climb back in mid-decade ifvendors solve connectivity problems, indigestion (improper assimilation ofexisting systems), and create new technological drivers.andM;The Gartner Group forecasts that the hot products of the decade will bepalm-top computers, wireless phones, image management, object-orientedprogramming, speech recognition, RISC and parallel processors, optical disks,fiber optics and SONET.andM;Worldwide micro, mini and mainframe computers will grow from about $300billion this year to almost $700 billion by the year 2000, the companypredicts.andP;  Further, the gap between micros, workstations and mainframes willwiden 24 percent each year over the next ten years, resulting in 700 moreMIPS for each $1 spent on microcomputers vs.andP;  mainframes by the year 2000.andM;The Gartner Group says the under-$25,000 unit price market share will growfrom 45 percent in 1990 to 52 percent in 1995 and to 57 percent by 2000.andM;In the operating system arena, the company predicts that those which are&quot;open&quot; in the DOS, OS/2 and Unix arenas will be purchased for 60 percent oftotal systems by 2000 -- up from about 45 percent now.andM;The big winner of the 90s, it predicts, will be Fujitsu/ICL, which willsecond-best IBM and strengthen its grip on the number-two spot in theworld-wide data processing industry as it increases its market sharetwo-thirds by 2000.andM;(Wendy Woods/19901108/Press Contact: Kris Dale, 203/964-0096)</TEXT></DOC>